WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Okay, we're going.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Today is Tuesday, May 31, 2011.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:25.000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern oral history program at University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:36.000
I'm with filmmaker John Bishop in Selma, Alabama, where we are recording the oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:43.000
which is an undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture,

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:54.000
where especially happy to be here today with you Miss Avery, we're in Selma as I mentioned with Miss Annie Pearl Avery to talk about your life and work and engagement with SNCC and all your efforts in the struggle.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Thank you for welcoming us to Selma and we're really pleased to be with you.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Thank you.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Thank you. I'm pleased to meet you.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Let me start this morning just to have you talk a little bit about where you were born and where you came up a little bit about your family.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Well, I was born in Birmingham, Alabama,

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:31.000
and my mother and father were wheeled and headed townships.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:42.000
I was a first baby and my father was 54 years old when I was born. I was a first baby.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:58.000
But anyway, we were, I say we were, we were a poem. I'm poor now, but we were pulled in.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:22.000
But anyway, as time went on, in Birmingham, I had this situation where my aunt by the name had it and had it up in a Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania had a,

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:34.000
she and her husband didn't have any children, the husband deceased, and she wanted somebody to come stay with her.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And my mother had four of us, so my mother decided to share me with her for a few years.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:53.000
That was your great aunt. That was my great aunt. That was my mother's aunt, which had been my great aunt.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And during that time I was in Pittsburgh. I went to Gladstone Elementary, lived in Hazelwood.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I lived on Sylvan Avenue. I think it was Sylvan Road, Sylvan Avenue. Sylvan Avenue, I'm sure I'm dead.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But anyway, during that time, Emmett Till was murdered. And I guess you can say for a child, I was only about nine or ten years old when he was murdered.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:49.000
But the adults were in, you know, talking about it in the community and talking about it at my, at my home there, because my aunt had, had, had borders.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And they were talking about it and the way they were talking about it, they were just talking about a child.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
The only thing I could understand, get out of it, was the child had been murdered.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:11.000
A Negro child. And I, that's, I think that's what kind of peaked my interest.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Although I didn't understand lynching anything, but I did understand that a child was murdered and I was a child.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:31.000
And I was curious about this, the child being murdered. And I looked for a newspaper around the house, usually the newspaper would be there, because she had a board of, they bring newspaper.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:46.000
But I was head for the comics. And there was no newspaper that day. So I decided to go down to the, a little neighborhood grocery store where they had a, had a newspaper rack.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And I wanted to take a look at the paper. And I was from them with the paper and the, the, the store attendant told me I couldn't handle the paper unless I paid for it.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:18.000
But fortunately by me being the only child member in the family, period cousins and I had some, the cousins there, but they were adults.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:30.000
They spoiled me. They made sure I had pocket money to go to the movie. They made sure I had money to buy cookies and candy, bubblegum, whatever I wanted to do.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:56.000
So I paid for the paper. And when I see it now in a humorous type of way, I said, well, I sacrifice a nickel. And I can't remember which paper it was, whether it was the Pittsburgh, the regular paper, every day paper there would have, I'm not sure whether the Pittsburgh, Korea, Pittsburgh, Kuzat or something like that.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:15.000
It could have been, I'm not sure. But anyway, I tried to read this paper to try to understand the death of Emmett Till. But I still couldn't understand it really because I'm trying to understand it from a 9-10 year old point of view.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:38.000
The only thing I understood that it was a child murdered and it was a black child murdered. Later on, I'm back in Birmingham. And a man was murdered by the name of Mack Charles Parker, Poplarville, Mississippi.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:58.000
But I'm 14 years old now. And what happened is they had arrested him. Basically, the same type of thing that Emmett Till was murdered for making insult and remarks to a white female or something like that.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And they arrested him, kept him in jail for a couple of weeks. And there were threats to take him out of jail. And I was keeping up with that too. And then, all of a sudden, they went in and took him out of jail and killed him.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:31.000
And right after that, there are a lot of other things begin to happen. The bus boycott in Montgomery, Autherine Lucy trying to enter the university, Ole Miss.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Reverend Shuttlesworth, right there in Birmingham, along with Reverend Charles Billups and Reverend Oliver and Reverend (J.L.) Phifer. These are the ministers that I remember that we're trying to desegregate the schools there in Birmingham.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:08:19.000
Matter of fact, specifically, I think he was trying to desegregate Phillips High School, which my children graduated, both of my boys graduated from. But anyway, these things went on. And then after that came the cityans and the freedom rise. And I was really excited at that point, but I'm 16 years old now. So I understand this from a different level.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And on the news, I was hearing about young people being involved and young people were in the change. And I was young and I wanted to get involved.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:46.000
So what I did is, I said, I wanted to go with them. I wanted to get involved. I wanted to go with them. And I didn't know whether they were going to come to Birmingham or what.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
You mean freedom rise?

00:08:48.000 --> 00:09:05.000
I'm speaking of the freedom rise. And when they got to, in Atlanta, I think, and they said they were coming to Birmingham, then I purchased a ticket from Birmingham to Montgomery.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And not long after I purchased a ticket, and I remember the bus arriving, about the bus arriving in Anniston, Alabama, and was blown up in Anniston, Alabama.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And then they came on to Birmingham. But you know, during that time they had two bus stations. They had Trailways and they had greyhound.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And Trailways was one that I was not that familiar with. I was more familiar with the greyhound bus station.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And I found out later on, why I was, I thought about later on, why I was in really more attracted to the greyhound bus station. My grandfather, my dad is father.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:06.000
When he got older, he couldn't go anywhere by himself because he'd get lost. What some of us had to be with him. He was always going to the greyhound bus station.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:19.000
But anyway, this is where I, you know, I kind of wanted to be. So I went that ticket and everything.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:34.000
So when they got to Birmingham, and I went down to the greyhound bus station, along with a young lady at that time, that lived in the projects when I was a little girl.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Her name was Candace Grindes. Candace. Now Candace told me that her uncle was Reverend Abernathy.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:57.000
But I didn't know this. You know, who Reverend Abernathy was. It was really running that important. To me, Abernathy, okay.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:08.000
But we had decided to go down to the greyhound bus station to take a look. But what happened is it was roped off.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Then I wanted to go. I went down there. I think the next night after, and I talked. I met a guy by the name of Wilson Brown.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:30.000
And Wilson, I think, was some kind of a part of a welcoming committee or something named Birmingham. I'm for the freedom writers when they got in.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And I told him I wanted to go. And Wilson said, okay, he started talking to me about nonviolence. I didn't understand nonviolence.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:50.000
But when I bought the ticket, I had bought me a knife to go with the ticket, because I'm going to protect myself on the bus.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And Wilson told me I couldn't go because I didn't understand the concept of nonviolence. And I asked him what the nonviolence means.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:10.000
He said, this is when someone hit you, you can't hit them back. I said, I don't think I want to do that. So I got a refund for my ticket.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:29.000
And later on, I was seeing Wilson every night or every other night coming into the, the, uh, A.G. Gaston that lounge, which was a special spot for my, uh, my friends and myself, my other girlfriends and myself.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And, um, one night Wilson asked me not long after that, the, the, that I want to go to a student nonviolent coordinate committee meeting in Atlanta.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:51.000
Well, the thought was I said, well, I never been to Atlanta before. And now I'm going to get a chance to go free.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Plus I want to learn more about what was going on in the civil rights movement. And I told him, yes, I left my knife at home.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
And everything is history after that.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
That was your first big move towards direct involvement?

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:15.000
Yeah, that was the first, first big movement towards getting involved in the move and in the civil rights movement.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:21.000
I came to the meeting before we tell the Atlanta story. I want to ask a couple of things.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:34.000
Um, I have a note from the research that I did in preparing for the session that in the late 50s, you've become quite interested and considered joining and perhaps, um, did become a member of the nation of Islam.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Well, what happened is, um, I made my first, um, contact with people in the nation of Islam when Mack Charles Parker was in jail before he was murdered.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:14:11.000
And they were the only had the Muhammad Speaks. And this was the only paper that had the head something meaningful about this man every day in the paper, even up till the time he was murdered and even after he was murdered.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:19.000
And this is what attracted me to them because this was something visible that I had seen so going on.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
Well, I saw something going on, I should say.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And I started going to some of the meetings and the thing about this was that, um, they weren't visible enough for me.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Maybe it just wasn't enough activity, which, um, I'm not saying that what they were doing wasn't important.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:53.000
But it just, it just wasn't enough activity going on around it for me.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:11.000
I guess I wanted more action and I saw more direct action with, um, the civil, the, the sit and the Freedom Rides, although I know core was a part, more part of some of the Freedom Rides itself.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:23.000
But the thing about this is they, they just, so, so I went with what, what was more, more active, visibly active.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:30.000
Then, um, can I ask you, I'm just before you're about to head for that sneak meeting at Atlanta.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:40.000
What was your life like in Birmingham? What can you describe the community, the, the things that, um, were taking up your time, the, what you were witnessing in the community?

00:15:40.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Well, I was riding the back of the bus and I don't know maybe, maybe this thing of living in Pittsburgh, um, and living under different conditions might have made, made the difference because, um, when I went to Pittsburgh and we got to, um, Cincinnati, I think.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:08.000
And my aunt told me I could sit anywhere I wanted to sit.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:17.000
But I still, they still didn't don't know me because you have to remember I'm only nine or ten years old and sitting in the way I wanted to sit.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:25.000
It really didn't, although in Birmingham, when I got on the bus, I saw the science in color.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:42.000
But it still wasn't, you know, didn't, wasn't as meaningful. But then once I got to Pittsburgh and associating with the other children, it's really who I learned a lot of stuff because they were saying, don't say yes, sir.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:56.000
And no, sir is yes and no. And they would tell me about how to, I'd go to the store to ask for a drink, orange drink. And they said, don't ask for a drink. You asked for a pop.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And I just found out just about four weeks ago, why they calling a pop, you know, what started them calling these things a pop.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:25.000
But anyway, I, um, I changed a lot there. And I guess the coming back to Birmingham and then going back to riding the back of the bus, and I went to integrated school now.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:45.000
In Pittsburgh. And it was different. One perfect, but it was different. And, um, this, I guess this is what motivated me to probably get involved.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
What do you think about some of the trips to Atlanta?

00:17:48.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Well, the trip to Atlanta, when I got to Atlanta, um, and I met people, met, met people there, um, that eventually, um, I became friends with and affected my whole life.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:23.000
And actually in terms of the idea of meeting some decent white people, because I'd never met any decent white people to know them until I got to that meeting.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:43.000
And in Anne Braden (likely), I met, uh, Bob Zellner, I met Dottie Miller Zellner, who became a dottie Zellner later on. I met Penny Patch, I met Bill Hansen, and there was a lot of other people I met.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:19:06.000
And, um, and even the blacks that I met, I met Ms. Ella Baker, I met James Forman, I met Ruby Doris Smith, um, I met Julian Bond, I met so many, so many people, um, that I hadn't, had never met before.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:15.000
And I, I guess you can say I went into it, uh, from a learning, from a learning stage.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:23.000
Uh, I never knew anything I did was going to be important.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:26.000
So that was an annual meeting last of what a couple of days?

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:46.000
Uh, this one, I think for a, a couple of days of weekend or something like that, because at that time, SNCC had their first, their first office was on Auburn Avenue upstairs over the Atlanta Daily World, where the Atlanta Daily World was on Auburn Avenue.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Uh, and it had holes in the floor. You know, we had to be careful, but we went upstairs, but we had to be careful about where we walked, you know, because the big hole in the floor they were doing constructions, something on the bill.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:17.000
Yeah, and then we went, it went from there to Raymond Street, but, um, anyway, after that Atlanta meeting, um, matter of fact, on the way back home, we got in trouble.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:22.000
And almost got murdered right there in Marietta, Georgia.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:37.000
Well, what we did is we got confused trying to get back to Birmingham, Wilson Brown, Nathaniel Lee, and there was a white girl that wanted to meet Reverend Shuttlesworth.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:50.000
No, I never, no, no, because I never saw her again. She wanted to meet Reverend Shuttlesworth and myself. That's what we, we, we were all in the car together.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:54.000
And she had been at the SNCC meeting too.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And we got confused and ended up in Marietta, Georgia.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:05.000
And we said, well, let's go in the bus station and get some inspiration.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:16.000
What we went into bus station, and now we in trouble, because we go into bus station, and these people see this white girl with us.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:27.000
And during that time, if you were in a mixed group together, you were considered part of the civil rights movement.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:31.000
Which I didn't know at the time, it hadn't really thought about it at that point.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:39.000
But this is what the situation was when we left the bus station, the police followed us.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:44.000
And when the police were, we still don't know where we're going. And we couldn't find any black people.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:53.000
Just ask, we didn't see any black people. And we got stopped.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:58.000
We hadn't done anything, but we got stopped. Police pulled us over.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:08.000
And by being Marietta, Georgia, I'm saying it was just like, you go two blocks and you're out of the sit limits.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:16.000
And all you headed out of the other area there, and what happened is the police stopped us.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:23.000
Arrested Wilson, commented the car.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:30.000
And now, we don't have no way to get around. And Wilson's in jail.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:34.000
And we've standing out on the street trying to figure out what to do.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:38.000
Try to find a black community, no black folk.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:43.000
And I said, let's go back to the bus station.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Because we can still see the bus station right there. Once we got back into the sit, they made Wilson drive his car with us in it.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:56.000
Put us out. Take Wilson to jail. Take the car.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:03.000
And there we are. And we decided to go to the bus station finally.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:08.000
And we got to the bus station. The attendant told us we couldn't stay.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.000
Because we weren't customers.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:19.000
I said, I thought about it. I said, just by tickets.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Back to it. We couldn't back tickets too far. Back to Atlanta.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:29.000
Anything. But this made us, because I understood the part about the, what was it?

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:36.000
In a state chamber, commerce, the law is, they had to, you know, once we became customers,

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.000
since they said we weren't customers, okay, we'll become customers.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
And you still were traveling freely?

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:45.000
Yeah. And that way they couldn't kick us out of the bus station.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:55.000
And we stayed in the bus station there. And what we did is right after that, we called back to the SNCC office

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:00.000
and talked to someone there.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:06.000
I think, you know, I don't know who we talked to now. I forgot now.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:12.000
But anyway, we talked to someone. But during that time, if you remember, they had switchboards.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:21.000
You couldn't dial directly out, you had a switchboard. And we were using the payphones in the bus station.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:28.000
And finally, but this was a way to communicate at least let folks know where we were.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:39.000
And by this time, it's about dark. Dark, just got dark. And it was really, really frightening.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:55.000
It wasn't too frightening at first. It was kind of like kind of odd, but not too frightening.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:25:03.000
Until it got darker and we got crowd, crowd, people crowded. But only white people.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:08.000
More and more people, that bus station probably had had that many people in it.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:18.000
And the people in it, in the history of the Marietta, Georgia. But it had a lot of people at night.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:28.000
And one white girl. And we started getting phone call.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:32.000
When we first said figure out where we were going to take a refuge, we didn't know where it was.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:39.000
Three phone booths there. We decided we were going to take a phone booth in peace if things got worse.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:45.000
Well during that time, they had phone booths. You know, when you used the phone, they had a booth.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:48.000
The door was closed on it.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
So you were thinking each to get inside a walk-on and close the door?

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:55.000
Yeah, we got three, three, three booths. You all got a booths.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:01.000
This was going to be our refuge. But in the meantime, we were getting called.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:08.000
We're back on after short break. I mean the sun was.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:11.000
So you were just getting in.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
Miss Avery, you were just...

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Well, I was just getting into the part about the switchboard.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:23.000
You know, they had switchboards in.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:24.000
Yes.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:30.000
And in order to get a call out, you had to go through a switchboard.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:42.000
And not long after we made the call, obviously they must have called a Associated Press.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:49.000
'Cause at that time, I think Julian was... Julian Bond was on the staff of Atlanta.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:54.000
Inquirer. Is it Atlanta inquirer?

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:59.000
Anyway, he was on the staff of some of the small black newspaper.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:03.000
And what he did, what they did was...

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
The Associated Press started calling us.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:07.000
Asked...

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
On the pay phone.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:13.000
They started calling us asking us where we are okay.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:18.000
Every few minutes they called back and asked where we are okay.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
But the thing about this is...

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
I don't think nobody could have gotten to us.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:31.000
I think if we had stayed there longer than we did, just so happened.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.000
We were there until probably about 12 o'clock that night.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:38.000
But the later it got the worst these people got.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
And more hostile they became.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:45.000
They got sticks and started beating on the seats.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:50.000
And shouting all kind of synergies and threats.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
They were going to kill us.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
And calling the white girl a nigger level.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.000
This kind of stuff.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:00.000
And we're going to kill y'all niggas tonight.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:07.000
And the later it got, the more frightening it got.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:13.000
And finally, Julian Bond and some other people showed up.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.000
I think Howard Moore...

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:20.000
He was one of the slick lawyers.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:25.000
And he finally married Julian, sister Jane.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:35.000
But James Forman, Julian, Howard Moore, and a few other people came along.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:40.000
I think with some people from the Justice Department to get Wilson out of jail

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:48.000
and get us out of there and form it decided we shouldn't try to go to Birmingham

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:52.000
that night, stay in Atlanta and then go to Birmingham during the day.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.000
How did they do with the crowd when they got there?

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:00.000
How did they find their way in to get you and extract you from being surrounded by that crowd?

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:08.000
Well, we don't really know, except they came in and told us we can, you know, let's go.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
You know, after they got Wilson out of jail, they came to work.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:16.000
Because the town is, these jailers on the corner, Graham bus station probably,

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:21.000
you know, when I can visualize it now, just probably across the street.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:27.000
Because we can see the Graham bus station from the jailhouse on the corner.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:30.000
And it wasn't that far.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:34.000
Did they come back with any vocal sheriffs from police officers?

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:35.000
No.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
No, never happened.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.000
So they just on their own authority.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:43.000
Well, the people who came came from Atlanta.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:46.000
They didn't come from Marietta.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.000
These were people who came in from Atlanta.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:55.000
And I think it was part of the Justice Department, a member of something from the Justice Department.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
But they had somebody from the Justice Department.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:58.000
I think so.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:03.000
They had a black car, they had black cars, they had government cars, they had all of black.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:10.000
But I'm assuming it was, anyway, somebody from the Justice Department came there to assist us.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:15.000
That person, why the Justice Department?

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:19.000
I think so.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:20.000
It's a lot of stuff.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:27.000
It's kind of vague in it except for the party in the bus station.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:36.000
Tell me about the impact on you was at being in such a very fearful situation.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:51.000
Well, I knew that it was very, very good chances of getting really hurt or keeled.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:31:02.000
But on the other hand, I learned to keep become and use my head when I'm in a situation.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.000
And that's in any situation.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:14.000
I applied it today because going to that bus station was the best thing we could do instead of trying to look for a black community.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
We don't know where the black community is.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.000
We didn't see any black people.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
The bus station we could see that.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:28.000
Then when they told us we couldn't stay and we had, you know, when it came to me quick to get the tickets.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:29.000
Let's get the tickets.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
We got the tickets.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
We weren't out of harm's way.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:40.000
But we were in a situation and out of rubber being there and out on the road somewhere, when it got dark.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
It's a good thing they did stop us before it got dark.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:53.000
You see, because stopping us out on the road with no communication, nobody around at all, even if they were bad people.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
It's better to have some people around.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:08.000
But anyway, it was just something that I learned learned early on in terms of some of the things that I did later on that probably saved my life.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:14.000
Now, when we finally got the Birmingham, we met Reverend Shuttlesworth.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:18.000
And this was my first time meeting Reverend Shuttlesworth.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:19.000
Right?

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.000
And he heard about what had happened in America?

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:29.000
No. Wilson called him and told him he had somebody to watch the meeting.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:35.000
And we went to his place and he was still in his pajamas when we met him.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:42.000
And this was my first time meeting him, being right there in Birmingham, but all this activity going on.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:46.000
This was the very first time I met Reverend Shuttlesworth.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:52.000
And not long thereafter, I think you participated in the sit in the war?

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:56.000
You participated in a sit at the war?

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:57.000
Yeah.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:04.000
He had me down at the World War II because we were going to test the sit ends there.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:16.000
And we went to, I think it was the war worth, the creases, or one of the places, I think it was World War.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:29.000
And from when we went in there and Wilson and Reverend Shuttlesworth and Reverend Charles Billups were standing on the side.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:37.000
And the group of, I guess this was a, I think this was the very first sit in that Birmingham had.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:40.000
And we were going to test the sit end.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:45.000
Well they didn't, so they didn't arrest us, but they didn't serve us.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:54.000
But what happened is they had a white fellow that was going down the counter, spitting, and pulling ketchup.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:57.000
And I hadn't quite been adjusted to this nonviolent thing.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:07.000
I wasn't sure how I was going to react to this spitting and being, you know, pulling ketchup and Reverend Shuttlesworth.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:11.000
Somehow I was active and I was, you know, and he said, come here.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:29.000
I want you to stand here beside me because I hadn't really learned much about the nonviolence thing to really want to use it as a tactic or anything.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:33.000
I hadn't learned enough about it to accept it for any reason.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:36.000
But I wanted to go sit on the lunch counter.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:41.000
And I told Reverend Shuttles, I want to go back up there. He said, you can't go.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:43.000
He didn't stand right here with me.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:50.000
But anyway, later on, I went to, I think of an Albany, Georgia.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:57.000
I don't know what that went there then or either had, anyway, I got arrested in Albany, Georgia.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:02.000
And I think we had an attorney named by the name was CB King.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:12.000
And there were some other people I met. The first people I met were Ruth, I met Rutha Mae Harris.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:19.000
I met, I think, Bernice Johnson Reagon.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:24.000
And I met Charles Sherrod.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:30.000
I think, yeah, I had already met him up in the, and I met Bob Mants.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:38.000
Bob Mants. And, Rev. Prathia Hall.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:42.000
And I'm trying to thank some of the people that I met.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:48.000
Can you tell me a little bit about your impression of these people, these other folks like yourself,

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:53.000
who are making up, snickering these days, and what they were like and what you liked about them,

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:57.000
what you didn't like about them, what attracted you to them?

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:03.000
Well, what attracted me was, is mostly just, you know, I've met these people,

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:08.000
and they were already involved. So I was like, in a learning stage,

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.000
I thought I considered myself being in a learning stage at all the time,

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:19.000
it was something I could learn from them, and, or, participate.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:27.000
But mostly it was an educational thing for me, because some of these people even had higher education,

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:34.000
and education in Adi, but I was getting educated too, just being there with them,

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:39.000
and just talking with them, and exchanging ideas, just asking them,

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:44.000
I said very little during that time.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:50.000
Did you feel, when you were getting involved in the process directly,

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:58.000
did you feel, I wonder how, what, what the emotional experience of going through a protest

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.000
with a lot of hostility around you, was like for you?

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:07.000
Did you feel a lot of anger, did you feel a lot of fear, did you feel calm?

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:12.000
What was the mix of emotions for you in a situation like that?

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:18.000
Well, the thing about anger, I had been in this environment so long,

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:25.000
I've seen, you know, I didn't walk around being angry all the time.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:35.000
It might have been emotional, even just one to achieve something and do,

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:45.000
and one thing should be better, basically, because I guess because I had been exposed to a different situation,

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:50.000
you know, they say, slave, and it's slave, no, be slave, no more.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:55.000
If you've been free, you don't want to be slave anymore, so I guess that psychologically

00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:02.000
that might have, in my subconscious probably had a lot to do with it.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:10.000
I can't say which one thing, or a combination of things,

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:17.000
I really can't, can't say, except I can just probably pinpoint some things

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:21.000
and say that this probably was what happened.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:28.000
And I'm just realizing that in the last few months, a few years,

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:34.000
that these are the kind of things that probably brought me to do with idea.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:38.000
When you were down to Albany, was your status, what was your status for SNCC,

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:41.000
were you a volunteer or were you getting paid?

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:46.000
No, I was a volunteer. I don't think anybody was getting paid at that time.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:53.000
But they finally, somehow another, because this thing, but it's probably too good to be true.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:39:04.000
I guess the government, everybody else thinks this was a way to also disqualify SNCC,

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:14.000
and the younger groups, because where can you get people who want to go to jail,

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:20.000
take a risk on their life, and don't get paid.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:27.000
We were going to people's houses, staying with them, and helping do the housework,

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:34.000
and stuff like this, and then do voter registration too, and do the demonstrations

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:39.000
or whatever was going on that support the community.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:45.000
So it's kind of strange that they asked, I think we were getting,

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:52.000
they finally forced them into giving us $10 a week, I think it was.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:40:02.000
Which is still nothing, but it was just a way to probably make us use our funds.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:09.000
What are some of the things that come first in mind when you think about going down to Albany that first time,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:17.000
Charles Sherrod and the other folks are down there, and they put the Albany moving together?

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:23.000
Well, I wanted to find out what Georgia, I think they were, I think,

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:28.000
Bob Mantz was in America, as I believe.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:37.000
But what happened is, I was just there to assist in whatever they wanted me to do.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:43.000
Pretty much, that's basically what I did during that time.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:47.000
Tell me more or tell, how you spent your time?

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:49.000
What was it like to go out to do voter registration?

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:57.000
Well, I did, I think I tried to do voter registration one day, and the next day I went on the demonstration,

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:09.000
and I got locked up, and I was in there for, I don't know, it was quite some time, I was about three or four weeks, I guess.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:13.000
Tell me about, if you do it, what was it like to do in the jail?

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:17.000
What's the whole experience like to be in jail at that time in that kind of place?

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:24.000
Well, I was in there for something good and important, I thought.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:42.000
But what happened is, I really, just in order to adapt to this situation, I just really kind of put it in the back of my mind,

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:53.000
and I was going on outside and tried to adapt to the environment around me, I was able to get some,

00:41:53.000 --> 00:42:02.000
some packages of cigarettes and stuff like this, anything that I could read or something,

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:13.000
that's how I adjusted, I just immediately adapted, and I guess that's probably one of the things that I've been good at,

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:24.000
is adapting to my environment, at all times, with an NGO or out of jail, I adapt to my environment.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:36.000
I'm going to ask about the episode, experience you had when after William Moore,

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:41.000
was a white postal fairy, actually, through the march and was killing their Gadsden.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
Guests in Alabama?

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:44.000
Yeah.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:49.000
And there was someone certain to be about what, not Smith, was how they would respond,

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:52.000
and you had a choice about how they respond to you.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:53.000
Did you talk about that?

00:42:53.000 --> 00:43:01.000
Yeah, well, they had decided on what they were going to do, and my position was to go,

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:09.000
do what William Moore was doing, to finish what he started, even if I had to finish it alone.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:15.000
And I didn't realize when I decided to make a decision to do this,

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:22.000
that I was really actually taking on the march the way he did it alone.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:29.000
I just didn't realize it, I just figured that we needed to go ahead and march.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:36.000
And my intention was to go with other people, but I didn't know how long it was going to be before,

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:41.000
either weather level was going to go at all because it was so much, it was a dilemma,

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
and so much discussion about it.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:50.000
And I made a decision to get me a sign and go on the way you're more of march.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:57.000
I was arrested a few minutes later after I started walking with the sign,

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:09.000
and I was placed in jail in Gaston, Alabama, where the next day or two some other people were arrested.

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:19.000
And the females, I had no other arrested, were Diane Nash,

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:24.000
I believe it or not, Madeleine Sherwood, who was one of the movie stars,

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:33.000
she came down and she was arrested in the William of March.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:42.000
She played in what if the Cat on a Hot Tin Roof, she played the pregnant woman on the hot tin roof,

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:48.000
and she came down and she bundled it out right away.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:55.000
She was on a white female in the group, I think, and she was bonded out right away,

00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:04.000
but Diane and two other young ladies from Birmingham were locked up,

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:09.000
and they put them in a cell, I think, next to me.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:14.000
But before that, they were trying to interrogate me and try to find out how I got there,

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:18.000
and they told me, I didn't give them any information, I told them,

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:23.000
I just might, take me on into the cell and put me in the jail,

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:26.000
or do whatever y'all gonna do, because I ain't talking.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:30.000
I never did tell them how I got there, who brought them?

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:35.000
Or what the details, no details at all.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:41.000
And later on, we were moved to, with Tutwiler,

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:44.000
and then they were like, they were in there for about ten weeks,

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:50.000
we were in there quite a while together, for that I can't be exact.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:46:01.000
But they moved us to with Tutwiler, because it was supposedly a threat to come in the jail and take us out,

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.000
and took, and do what's in.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:12.000
And so the young men who barred, they took them to Kilby, and took us to with Tutwiler,

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:16.000
and when we got to with Tutwiler, they put us in a hole,

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:22.000
the first night we stayed in a hole, then they put us in the hospital,

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:26.000
with the people in the hospital, although we were sick,

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:30.000
but I guess they decided that this is the best place for us to be,

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:33.000
so we would stir up any trouble in jail.

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:35.000
So they put you in the hole?

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:38.000
It was a hole, we had to crawl.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:46.000
It was a seal, it was dark, and it was a hole like,

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:53.000
because we really couldn't stand up in there, it was dark.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:57.000
I don't think I remember it was dark in there,

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.000
and we could maneuver around, I guess they had us in there for,

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:04.000
in that particular area for a reason, that night.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:11.000
But then the next morning, when they moved us to the hospital part of jail,

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:14.000
and one of the women who were bringing around the trays,

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:21.000
it was a trustee, she was bringing the trays for the sick people in the hospital,

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:25.000
and she asked us, she said, where are y'all from?

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:29.000
We knew the freedom fighters were here,

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:32.000
and they didn't want us to know, but we knew about it, everybody knows.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:35.000
That's what the lady said, she said, everybody knows.

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:38.000
So she asked us, where were we from?

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.000
She asked Diane, Diane said, Nashville,

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.000
the other two girls said, Birmingham, I said Birmingham,

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.000
and I asked her, wherever she from, she said, Tuscaloosa,

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:50.000
and she said she was in there for life.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:53.000
Some guy she was with.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:58.000
You mentioned that, you mentioned a moment ago that,

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:01.000
after more was killed,

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:04.000
that there was a lot of discussion as to what to do,

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:07.000
and they decided to go forward more.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:10.000
You mentioned earlier too that,

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:14.000
when your first encounter, these are about nonviolence of a strategy,

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:19.000
and the movement, you know, had some skepticism about that in some way.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:22.000
Can you explain a little bit about how your perspective,

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:27.000
how your opinions and viewpoints compared to the ones that you saw in SNCC in these years?

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:34.000
Did you feel sometimes that there was some difference between your instincts

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:39.000
about how to do things and what SNCC was doing?

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:44.000
Well, I can only speak to individuals,

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:50.000
because there were certain individuals who took this on as a way of life.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:58.000
I was just one of those people among others who did not adopt nonviolence as a way of life,

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:02.000
only as a tactic.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:05.000
Okay, we're back after short break.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:10.000
Miss Avery, we'll build the story towards all the way up to room beyond Selma,

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:15.000
but I want to ask now, 60, say, 62, 63.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:18.000
You haven't, you went into a number of different places for SNCC.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:23.000
Yeah. Can you skimps that out and talk about what you did and what you saw and how you felt?

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:30.000
And what those were very busy, busy years for SNCC, and you were right in the middle of that?

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:38.000
Well, what happened is I was then Birmingham too,

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:45.000
had been one of the first, one of our first demonstration, and was arrested.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:50.000
And then we were told that the decoy march, because what we did is,

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:57.000
Wyatt Tee Walker had me to go on the decoy march,

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:02.000
and it was only about 10 or 15 people,

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:06.000
and this was the throw, throw the police off,

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:10.000
because what they were doing is, if you marched,

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.000
you didn't have more marches.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:17.000
But a little bit of they know that the bigger march was coming later.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:25.000
And one of my best friends, I was talking to her, I said, you're going, I said, yes, I'm going.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:28.000
And she said, I ain't going.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:32.000
But on the second march, she came along, and I guess she did,

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:35.000
because there was so many other people,

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:39.000
who she was all the one going to be left out,

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:45.000
because they arrested the other people and myself,

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:52.000
and then later on, they showed up.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:55.000
And I said, what you're doing here, better?

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:01.000
She said, I said, but you said you didn't want to go, you wasn't going.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.000
She said, I wasn't going to be out there by myself.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:08.000
So I guess when several other people,

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:11.000
who I was associated with friends,

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:14.000
had decided they were going to go,

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:17.000
and she just said, she wasn't going to be alone,

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:21.000
she's about to go to.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:24.000
You were in Danville a while?

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:28.000
Yes, I was in Danville Virginia.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:33.000
I was arrested several times in Danville,

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:37.000
but I was arrested there,

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:40.000
and put in solitary confinement ahead,

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:47.000
a 90-day sentence for contempt of court in Danville.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:51.000
What was the judge's time to get back to work?

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:54.000
Well, we came to court.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:59.000
Matthew Jones, who just passed recently,

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:04.000
and was one of the freedom singers.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:14.000
Matthew, along with Avon Rollins, in Danville,

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:17.000
we were working in Danville together,

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:20.000
and I think it was some other guy there,

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:25.000
and came in from SCLC, and I can't think of what it meant.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:29.000
I might think of it in a minute, but anyway,

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.000
we'd gone to court on some cases.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:38.000
We had several cases already pending from jail.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:41.000
When we got there,

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:48.000
and it was crowded inside the courthouse,

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:53.000
and out in the hall, Matthew and I just showed up,

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:56.000
and looked in there, looked down,

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:58.000
and the trial, the court case,

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:03.000
already started, and the judge was asleep.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:06.000
Asleep! literally, sleep.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:08.000
You're not in there.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:11.000
I said, Matthew, see this?

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:14.000
He's asleep.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:17.000
I said to Matthew, let's wake him up.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:22.000
What we did is we went down to the front of the podium

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:27.000
where he was asleep and went limp.

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:31.000
Just laid down on the floor.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:36.000
He woke up, and he asked the police officers

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.000
standing on the side.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:41.000
He said, what's wrong with him?

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:42.000
The police officer said,

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:45.000
you're honored. That's what they call going limp.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:48.000
He was mad. He gave us 90 days.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:50.000
He wouldn't take it back,

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:56.000
so we had to serve our 90 days in solitaire from family.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:59.000
When I got out of jail,

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:03.000
for that particular incident,

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
Ava and Rollins,

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
who was project director at the time,

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
told me to go on and take a break.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:12.000
I go home to take a break.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:18.000
I get in the Birmingham late Saturday evening,

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
and I go to bed,

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.000
and what awakened me the next morning

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:25.000
was the bombing of the 16th Street Baptist Church.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:28.000
That's what awakened me.

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:32.000
I lived about 16 blocks

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:35.000
from there,

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:39.000
walked up to that time

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
on Sunday morning,

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:42.000
buses ran slow,

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:45.000
so I was able to walk

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
and wasn't there for it during that time.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:48.000
16 blocks,

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.000
18 blocks, nothing to walk.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:53.000
So I walked up to,

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:55.000
it's closest to the A.G. Gaston,

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:56.000
and motel,

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:00.000
and they had everything else roped off.

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:03.000
And soon after that,

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:06.000
Miss Ella Baker showed up.

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.000
Dr. King came in,

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:11.000
Reverend Abernathy.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:15.000
there was Jim Forman,

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.000
Andrew Young,

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:27.000
and this was the first time I met Larry Steele,

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:34.000
who was an editor of Jett at the time,

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:45.000
and things were emotional

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:48.000
because of the children being murdered.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:53.000
Later on that night,

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:55.000
we were in a room standing,

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
sitting down and talking,

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:03.000
and this is where we were in that room,

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:06.000
talking about things to do,

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:09.000
and we were pretty upset.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:12.000
We didn't which way to go.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:15.000
We weren't sure about just,

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:19.000
we weren't planning to do anything violent,

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:23.000
but we wanted to take some kind of direct action

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:30.000
that was more aggressive than just marching

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:37.000
and going to jail at that time.

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:41.000
Then I was in,

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:46.000
where was it?

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
Let me ask,

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:49.000
boy, think about that.

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:50.000
Let me ask the two other places,

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
if you work in Hale County.

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:53.000
Yeah.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:54.000
Can you work in that?

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
I will, Hale County,

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.000
a project director in Hale County,

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:01.000
on voter registration,

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:05.000
and that was before I came here,

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:09.000
but I was in Mississippi,

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:10.000
when the changes weren't in Goodman,

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
where murder I was in Clarksdale,

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:14.000
Mississippi,

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:18.000
and I went from Clarksdale to Natchez, Mississippi.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:23.000
I was arrested in Natchez, Mississippi.

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:31.000
I came here to organize voter registration project,

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:33.000
and there were several other friends of mine

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:34.000
that came in,

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:36.000
Cynthia Washington, I think,

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:37.000
was up in Greene County.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
Pitcher might have been in Perry County,

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:41.000
or Greene County.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
I think it was,

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.000
Perry County, Greene County.

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:48.000
And then,

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:52.000
they walked back on the after-show break,

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:58.000
talking about project director work in Hale County.

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:00.000
Can you tell me what,

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:03.000
what project director was like,

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:05.000
all the things that you were required to do,

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.000
and how you went about that work?

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.000
Well, what we did is,

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:12.000
we first, when you first scored a community,

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:16.000
we tried to find a place to stay in the community,

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:19.000
we let the community people know who we are,

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:21.000
and why we're there,

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:23.000
and find a place to live.

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:25.000
Sometimes we found places to live,

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
sometimes we didn't,

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:30.000
because of the fear of people,

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:37.000
but we were able to rent a house there in Hale County.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:39.000
And when we first went through the community,

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:42.000
we met some guy,

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:44.000
I don't know if a guy is in the,

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:46.000
he was a sergeant in the Army,

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:47.000
and he said,

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:48.000
he wasn't going,

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:51.000
he said, he didn't believe in everything we believed in,

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:56.000
and he said, he didn't believe in none violence.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:59:00.000
So, we still ask him to come to the mass me,

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:01.000
but lo and behold,

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:05.000
the first mass me being in the head,

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
when the meeting was over,

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:11.000
he was standing outside with his army right now.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:12.000
He said,

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:15.000
I just want to be sure everything was going to be alright.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:17.000
It's okay.

00:59:17.000 --> 00:59:24.000
And sometimes I know they said that we had,

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:25.000
but had guns,

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:27.000
but the thing is,

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:30.000
a lady by the name of Ms. Johnny May,

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:31.000
I forget her,

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:34.000
and Hale County said,

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:35.000
she said,

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:36.000
y'all have weapons.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:38.000
We said no.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:41.000
The two people were working during that time

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:42.000
with St. Clair,

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:43.000
Jetta, and myself.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:49.000
And he was the one taught me how to drive.

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:51.000
So, it's something happening to him.

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:53.000
I can see a drive to car.

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:56.000
And anyway,

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:58.000
they gave us a shotgun,

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.000
a 10 gauge shotgun.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
And so, every morning,

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:06.000
we got up.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:09.000
St. Clair was teaching me how to use a shotgun,

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:12.000
because as far as I told him how to hunt,

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:16.000
and just across the road from us,

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.000
it was a dead end street with them,

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:20.000
just across the road from us.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
There was a white family.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:26.000
They had a big fence up around their house.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:29.000
But the funny thing about it is,

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:32.000
us having that gun,

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:34.000
and him teaching me how to use it,

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:36.000
actually,

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.000
probably helped save us a lot of time,

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:40.000
because they probably said,

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:43.000
well, these people supposed to be known by them,

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:45.000
but they got a gun.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:48.000
And that's what I call minor justice.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:50.000
You know, he got a gun,

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:51.000
but they're not involved.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:53.000
Yeah, but they got a gun.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
You know, we went,

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:57.000
the registered people to vote,

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:00.000
we went to march at the Courthouse and stuff like that,

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:03.000
but these people got a gun.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:04.000
And you know,

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:06.000
in my opinion,

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:09.000
the clan and all of these people

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:11.000
who did all these evil things,

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:13.000
were cowards.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:16.000
So, a coward,

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:18.000
don't want to encounter nobody,

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
they're really can equal up to them.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:23.000
So,

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:26.000
just a psychological effect,

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:30.000
that they got a gun.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:32.000
And the only thing St. Clair was doing,

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:33.000
without the back door,

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:34.000
it was a big,

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:36.000
a long field of woods down in there.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:37.000
And he just said,

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:40.000
showing me how to hold a shotgun,

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:43.000
and how to use it.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.000
Did there ever come a time

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:47.000
where you picked up the gun

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:50.000
thinking you'd have to use it?

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:53.000
No.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:58.000
We had some sort of the same situation

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:00.000
in that specific.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:04.000
Chico Neblett was the project director there,

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:07.000
and we didn't have a place to stay.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:09.000
We stayed in the ladies room.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:11.000
She had a room,

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:12.000
that she was renting,

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:15.000
and she worked in a cafe at night,

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:17.000
and we slept there.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:19.000
So, we didn't have anywhere to go.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:20.000
People wouldn't look,

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:22.000
wouldn't give us a place to stay.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:24.000
And slick ended up buying a house there.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.000
I think the house was pretty cheap.

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:28.000
I think they got her about $3,000,

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:29.000
or something like that,

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:30.000
maybe less.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:31.000
You know,

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:33.000
but we did have a place to stay there,

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:37.000
but I came here after

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:40.000
a natural Mississippi to work

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:43.000
with on a voter registration.

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:45.000
And then when Jimmie Lee Jackson

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:48.000
had been killed here,

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:53.000
there was a decision

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:55.000
to the original decision

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:57.000
was to take his dead body

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:02.000
to Selma in a casket,

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:03.000
and finally,

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:05.000
it boiled down to us just marching.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:12.000
But now, the night before the march,

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:13.000
we got a call.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:14.000
The reason Dr. King,

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:16.000
because Dr. King was supposed to be here,

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:20.000
but he was not here.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:21.000
We got a call.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:23.000
We were in a strategy meeting

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:25.000
and sitting around talking,

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:28.000
and the following call came in directly

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:29.000
from Attorney General,

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:30.000
and the General,

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:31.000
Katzenbach's office,

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:34.000
saying that Martin's life was in danger.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:37.000
And we took Martin away from here that night,

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:40.000
and Hosea Williams and Andrew Young

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:43.000
flipped the call on who was going to represent

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:45.000
SCLC on the march.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:47.000
That's how Hosea Williams got that spot.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:49.000
That's the reason you see Hosea Williams

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:52.000
at the end in the parts.

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:54.000
And you'll see John Lewis

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.000
and you'll see (Amelia) Boynton

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:02.000
and Miss Marie Foster.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:06.000
And Marie Foster was one of the people

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:09.000
who marched all the way on the last march.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:10.000
The go back though,

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:11.000
I got arrested.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:13.000
He owned blood as Sunday.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:16.000
But I was the only person that got arrested.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:21.000
See, the intent was to terrorize us

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:25.000
and brutalize us.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.000
And strike fear,

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.000
and so much fear in us,

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:33.000
that we wouldn't want to march.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:36.000
Now, with all the police that they had,

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:38.000
and what they had,

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:42.000
the police land was the traffic light,

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:43.000
the first traffic light you get to

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:45.000
after you go across the bridge,

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:48.000
it was just about right along in that area.

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:50.000
Let me just mention,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:52.000
we turned the look over our shoulder

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:53.000
after the window.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:54.000
And you said you were straight out the window,

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:56.000
you could see that red.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:05:03.000
What happened is the head road blocked off.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:07.000
And their intention was really to hurt us.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:11.000
Now, before we marched,

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:14.000
myself and some other people came out

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:18.000
and drove around, took a look.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:22.000
Just to see what the situation was like.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.000
Scouting.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:25.000
Scouting, yeah.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:29.000
And we could see where the head had lined off.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:33.000
Not only that,

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:35.000
the reason I got arrested

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:39.000
was the police and I was having a physical disagreement

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:42.000
about where I wanted to be

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:45.000
and where he wanted me to be.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:48.000
'Cause after, I guess, the tear gas,

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:51.000
because I didn't get a fix to the tear gas.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:54.000
I was arrested pretty, pretty quick,

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:57.000
when the police and I had this difference

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:02.000
and taken on off the jail.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:05.000
But the intent was really to brutalize us

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:10.000
because if their intent was to stop us

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:12.000
and arrest us,

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:14.000
that was what they didn't arrest,

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:15.000
but me one.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:18.000
But most of the stuff that went on was beatings

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:20.000
and tear gas and...

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:23.000
And they even took pictures of it themselves.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:25.000
They took their own pictures of it.

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:27.000
If you go to the museum now

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.000
and you're seeing the bottom where it says

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:31.000
Alabama Department Department of Public Safety.

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:33.000
What we didn't have in the cameras anyway,

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:37.000
we couldn't afford the cameras.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:38.000
Because I've had people ask me,

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:40.000
say, where is your picture?

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:42.000
I said, no, tell them where I was.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:44.000
I said, we didn't take the pictures.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:46.000
And plus, I wasn't trying to stop

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:49.000
on any demonstration I was on.

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:54.000
I was just probably going to be part of it.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:58.000
See you March on 21st.

01:06:58.000 --> 01:06:59.000
Seven.

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:00.000
I marched on the seven.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:01.000
There were all three of them,

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:03.000
we had three marches.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:04.000
And then on the nine.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:05.000
Then on the nine.

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:07.000
And then on the final march.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:09.000
But I didn't walk all the way to Montgomery.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:12.000
What was your role?

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:15.000
Well, I was still...

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:18.000
Still, just project director.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:21.000
I was just a little bit more of a role.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:22.000
Of he, okay.

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:24.000
That's all I was.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:27.000
You know, a lot of...

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:30.000
The often would ask you to help with security.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:32.000
Like you mentioned going out scouting

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:37.000
and trying to get a sense of what might be waiting in terms of police response.

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:39.000
Is that a...

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:42.000
Or did you sometimes do some of that kind of work?

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:45.000
Not often, because I didn't drive.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:48.000
I just learned to drive.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:53.000
But I was sitting on certain...

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:55.000
I had certain things to do.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:56.000
From time to time.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:07:57.000
I was just chosen.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:07:58.000
I...

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:00.000
Not maybe out of the clear blue,

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:03.000
because the people knew who they were choosing to do.

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:05.000
Because right there in Birmingham,

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:11.000
the State Patrol were looking for Dr. King to give him an injunction.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:14.000
And I had just gotten out of jail in Birmingham.

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:19.000
And what they were trying to do is enjoying all the people who were marched.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:23.000
Or either they thought were going to march like Dr. King.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:27.000
And I'm sitting in the lounge there with my friend Betty and some other people.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:34.000
But Dr. Wyatt (Tee) Walker, Dr. Wyatt (Tee) Walker,

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:36.000
chose me to do this.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:43.000
But I think that I was chosen to do it because Betty couldn't have kept it quiet.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:46.000
You know, in hindsight, that's probably what it was.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:49.000
And he walked over to me and he whispered in my ear.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:50.000
And he said,

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:53.000
go around to rooms such as...

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:56.000
I forgot what the room was now.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:59.000
Go around there and tell them

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:02.000
that the police is out here looking for Dr. King.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:05.000
Said, Dr. King, round there, and the room, round there.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:06.000
He's round.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:08.000
They had registered in the master suite,

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:10.000
but he didn't wouldn't stay in the master suite.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:15.000
He was round in the room with Andy and Bernard Lee,

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:18.000
who was one of his lieutenants.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:25.000
And I discreetly and quietly got up and walked out.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:27.000
Told my friends I'd be back in a minute.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:33.000
Walked out, went around, told them to come back and sit down.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:37.000
That was part of the D-Core march and stuff like that.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:41.000
And I did stuff like that for the time and the time.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:47.000
Especially since we're right here looking at the window at the bridge.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:52.000
What are the memories come most vividly to your mind

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:57.000
and think about those three marches on that bridge?

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:01.000
Uh, really Sunday.

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:06.000
You know, what happened is after the march was over

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:10.000
and I finally got out of jail, but you know something?

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:13.000
This was the shortest time I'd ever stayed in jail.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:17.000
It was right here and so.

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:21.000
Atturning Peter Hall, barring the me out out of his pocket.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:22.000
That's what happened.

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:24.000
He came in from Birmingham.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:26.000
He was one of our attorneys.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:29.000
He came in and somebody had been looking for me

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:32.000
and somebody told him that I was in jail.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:34.000
And he came to the jail, barring me out,

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:39.000
got in his car, went back to Birmingham.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:42.000
Matter of fact, he was back in Birmingham before I was released.

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:44.000
They didn't release me right away.

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:47.000
I don't know why they kept me then to 11, 12 o'clock at night

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:50.000
because the barch had been over and stuff like that.

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:53.000
And I had been bond out long before that.

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:55.000
But they didn't release me until then.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:58.000
Maybe they thought I was going to get out there and join them again

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:00.000
as soon as they let me out or something.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:01.000
I don't know.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:03.000
I can only assume.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:08.000
But I just stayed in jail a few hours.

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:12.000
And that was phenomenal compared to all of the times

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:14.000
that I've been in jail.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:17.000
The longest time I've been in jail was in Danville, Virginia

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:22.000
and 90 days for Contemporary Court.

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:26.000
You think you're paying?

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:28.000
We're back after short break.

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:31.000
And one thing I know you wanted to share some thoughts about

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:34.000
was the election brothel.

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:37.000
Yes.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:44.000
Well, being the first African American president,

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:47.000
I never thought it would happen during my time.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:52.000
But if it did, always thought his name would be Charles, Joe,

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:56.000
John, Henry, Bob.

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:59.000
I never thought he would have an African name.

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:03.000
And that kind of excited me even more.

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:07.000
And I said to myself, this is my personal thought.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:12.000
I said, it don't get no better than this.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:18.000
And also that he was being elected on my 60-feet birthday.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:21.000
And you know when your 60-feet birthday, that's a turning point

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:22.000
in your life.

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:25.000
And I said, oh boy, this is real good.

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:31.000
Yeah, I was really excited.

01:12:31.000 --> 01:12:34.000
Not just about him being African American,

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:42.000
but because he has an African name, which was expected.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:49.000
At first when he said, oh no, we're going to have a problem.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:56.000
And I just, you know, it was just astounding just to think

01:12:56.000 --> 01:12:59.000
that it happened.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.000
I want to ask too.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:03.000
I got a few more things to ask you.

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:07.000
One is, you were relatively young when you first went to that

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:08.000
at land meeting.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:09.000
Yes.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:11.000
No, I was 16.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:13.000
Because you were only 16.

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:14.000
16?

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:16.000
You were on 43.

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:22.000
But I turned, I was 16, turned in 17 in November.

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:25.000
So when I got arrested, I was 17.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:30.000
But very first meeting then would have been still in 1960.

01:13:30.000 --> 01:13:31.000
Thanks for that.

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:34.000
Tell me the first meeting with SNCCP?

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:36.000
No, it would have been 61.

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:37.000
Yes, exactly.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:40.000
Okay, I thought you said 61.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:45.000
So you could still a very young person about 18, 17, 18.

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:56.000
And you were very quickly the moving whole time into a long, important roles for SNCCP.

01:13:56.000 --> 01:13:58.000
And you were the project director.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:08.000
I'm wondering about your feeling about your roles in the SNCCP and the roles of women in the SNCCP.

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:22.000
And how do you felt about how you were able to use your skills and your talents and your personality and all your efforts on behalf of SNCCP?

01:14:22.000 --> 01:14:25.000
Well, I didn't think too much of it over time.

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:27.000
I was just being myself.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:30.000
And I wasn't trying to start.

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:35.000
So I was just, but one thing I found out later on.

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:45.000
I didn't know who Harriet Tubman was, but I found out that I was a model and they Harriet Tubman when they come down to go in the jail.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:47.000
And the people would get in jail.

01:14:47.000 --> 01:15:04.000
And there was an experience of sometimes people, some people would maybe one individual would break down because the psychological effect of closing that iron door had an effect on you.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:24.000
If you didn't know how to adapt to that and take it and turn it into something, what you call a suffering for doing, getting something better done or getting something done that was good.

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:33.000
But what happened is, when people would come in and when somebody started that, as a, hey, no, we can't have that.

01:15:33.000 --> 01:15:36.000
But we have a problem in here.

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:38.000
We're in jail.

01:15:38.000 --> 01:15:46.000
And what happened is, the people who are jailers and stuff will take advantage of this and try to do things to frighten us.

01:15:46.000 --> 01:15:50.000
And this is one of the reasons you don't want to do this.

01:15:50.000 --> 01:15:56.000
And then the other prisoners in jail will think that they can run over us.

01:15:56.000 --> 01:16:08.000
So the best thing we can do if you feel like, you know, you want to cry, go in the closet, go in the, you know, you can call me and talk to me, don't, don't start that here.

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:10.000
And then nothing of one do it.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:19.000
Three or four of us might do it and start demanding to get out of jail because they don't ask if we're going to get us some cards.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:22.000
And then we'll get us some dominoes if we can.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:25.000
And sometimes we were able to do this.

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:27.000
And sometimes we had money on us.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:31.000
It wasn't much money, but remember now you're in jail.

01:16:31.000 --> 01:16:38.000
And if you want to get cigarettes and you got 50 cents, you can get a pack of cigarettes.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:41.000
Somebody'll get your pack of cigarettes.

01:16:41.000 --> 01:16:48.000
You know, things that, you know, if we were in a situation where you were allowed, because a lot of times we weren't allowed to have anything.

01:16:48.000 --> 01:16:50.000
Point blank, nothing.

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:54.000
But there were times when, you know, we were in jail.

01:16:54.000 --> 01:17:00.000
And there would be, when they come around, they didn't discriminate on that.

01:17:00.000 --> 01:17:03.000
They come around and say, well, who wants cigarettes?

01:17:03.000 --> 01:17:07.000
Or if they wouldn't get us a book or anything like that, we could get it.

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:13.000
And even if we had had a little money, we could get some information out.

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:20.000
You know, give somebody something to say, well, call this number until they're on the situation thing.

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:23.000
It's all right and things like that.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:27.000
And it was better to appear to be strong than to be weak.

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:32.000
So that's pretty much what I'm saying.

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:37.000
But I didn't understand that I call it now being a modern day, having a hair and a tuff.

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:43.000
But I didn't realize this at the time because I didn't know who hair it was.

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:45.000
And that's a last couple questions.

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:52.000
One is, what was your opinion of folks in SCLC compared to the folks in SNCC?

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:55.000
Did you have a, did you have a SNCC?

01:17:55.000 --> 01:17:57.000
Your work was so much better than SNCC.

01:17:57.000 --> 01:17:59.000
Did you have an opinion about the SCLC?

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:12.000
SCLC was had its place and so did SNCC and so did CORE,

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:15.000
And so did NAACP.

01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:23.000
But the older people, the more mature people wanted not to move so fast.

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:27.000
And the young people wanted to move now.

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:31.000
They didn't want to wait 20 years to come from the back of the bus.

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:35.000
They didn't want to wait 20 years to sit at a lunch cow.

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:48.000
And that's the reason, by me being young, I wanted to be a part of what the young people were doing.

01:18:48.000 --> 01:19:00.000
And the difference between SNCC and SCLC was that really SNCC and Corps were like the infantry.

01:19:00.000 --> 01:19:03.000
Because we went into places where you couldn't walk the street.

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:09.000
Forget about doing all care with Project, Rector, whatever you're trying to do, it ain't anything to happen.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:13.000
They were resting us just for being in town.

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:17.000
If you walk the street, you got to rest it.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:21.000
Anytime they decided to pick us up and the rest of this, what they did.

01:19:21.000 --> 01:19:22.000
Vagancy.

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:34.000
And we had to be careful not to get arrested for these kind of things if we could because we needed that funds to borrow out for something else.

01:19:34.000 --> 01:19:41.000
But getting arrested for vagueness is okay, everybody have 50% on them or whatever.

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:44.000
You had some money on it.

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:47.000
Which also worked for our advantage.

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:50.000
If we did go to jail, you had 50%.

01:19:50.000 --> 01:19:54.000
And you could do something with 50% don't sound like much now.

01:19:54.000 --> 01:20:02.000
But you could do much more than you think you could now with it in jail.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:03.000
So...

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:10.000
Did you have, could you have, make certain friends or have certain allies inside SNCC, that you met as much to you?

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:11.000
Yeah.

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:12.000
Who was that?

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:19.000
Well, one of the persons that I was really...

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:25.000
I could sit in gym, Jim Forman (and is/was) elevator, my mentor.

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:36.000
But people like my friends were especially people that I worked personally with.

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:52.000
And Janet Moses, Ruby Sales, Gwen Patton, Bob Manes.

01:20:52.000 --> 01:20:56.000
You could say, Julian, you know, the people that I...

01:20:56.000 --> 01:21:10.000
Ruby Doris Smith, Prathia Hall, Sam Block, James Peacock and Willie Peacock.

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:13.000
James is dead now.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:17.000
They both came to James Peacock, Willie Peacock.

01:21:17.000 --> 01:21:20.000
And Sam Block came from Mississippi.

01:21:20.000 --> 01:21:30.000
Frank Smith, who has a museum up in Washington, a slavery civil war museum, Charles Sherrod.

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:36.000
All of the people that I knew, Charles Jones, there's a whole lot of people that I knew.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:40.000
Dottie Zellner, Bob Zellner.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:44.000
Over a period of time, you know, you get to know people, you see them all the time.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:57.000
And when you work with them, you get to have a certain bond, constantly, who's one of my best friends?

01:21:57.000 --> 01:22:01.000
She came in from California to work.

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:08.000
She worked mostly out of Atlanta office, but Judy Richardson.

01:22:08.000 --> 01:22:11.000
Of course, Judy and I went to jail again.

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:19.000
That's another thing a lot of us who went to jail together and spent time in jail together.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:23.000
I didn't know much about Diane, except for what I heard.

01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:26.000
But I'm saying we spend 10 weeks in jail.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:31.000
You really, really, really, really gonna get to know somebody in 10 weeks.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:33.000
What is the question?

01:22:33.000 --> 01:22:36.000
What was your describe?

01:22:36.000 --> 01:22:49.000
I describe her as a strong black female.

01:22:49.000 --> 01:23:03.000
Probably, she was much more forceful than some other people.

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:08.000
And by me, I won't be forceful myself and do it.

01:23:08.000 --> 01:23:12.000
I'm probably just wanting to see things go ahead.

01:23:12.000 --> 01:23:17.000
These are the people that I look kind of looked up to.

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:29.000
And especially the people in Mississippi, because Mississippi was really a hard case going to Mississippi.

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:37.000
Matter of fact, one of the worst things that was one of the most frightening times in my life in the Civil Rights Movement was in the Mississippi and Clarks there.

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:45.000
The night that the clan surrounded our office, they had a curfew on black people.

01:23:45.000 --> 01:23:52.000
Couldn't be on the street after 12 midnight.

01:23:52.000 --> 01:23:56.000
And 11, 15, 11, 30, you had to be here at home.

01:23:56.000 --> 01:24:00.000
The clan surrounded our office one night.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:03.000
We couldn't leave.

01:24:03.000 --> 01:24:06.000
And we didn't want to stay.

01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:08.000
And we couldn't see the faces or anything.

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:12.000
The only thing we could see was headlights.

01:24:12.000 --> 01:24:15.000
Now we knew there weren't any black people out there doing this.

01:24:15.000 --> 01:24:17.000
It was white folks.

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:21.000
They had headlights and they were screaming, it's shouting all kind of representatives.

01:24:21.000 --> 01:24:23.000
And this went on all night long.

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:32.000
The only thing we had to guard was under a desk, under a table or something.

01:24:32.000 --> 01:24:43.000
Lafayette Surney was the guy who was headed the project there.

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:52.000
After 65, and after the voting, my dad passed it in some of the 65.

01:24:52.000 --> 01:24:57.000
What's your role with Step from 65 forward?

01:24:57.000 --> 01:25:00.000
Well, we kind of thought everything.

01:25:00.000 --> 01:25:01.000
At least I did.

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:03.000
I guess you could say we dropped about.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:10.000
We thought things were going to get better, things were going to be all right.

01:25:10.000 --> 01:25:18.000
Because when I finally went to New York and stayed, I think it was 67.

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:22.000
I was around the New York SNCC office.

01:25:22.000 --> 01:25:25.000
It was still SNCC.

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:29.000
It's been SNCC all the time.

01:25:29.000 --> 01:25:33.000
Only because SLC didn't put me on stab.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:35.000
That's one of the only reasons.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:42.000
There was another thing as they were older and more mature.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:50.000
And just like I said, a lot of the places that we were in, a lot of places, Dr. King,

01:25:50.000 --> 01:25:52.000
just about all the places.

01:25:52.000 --> 01:25:59.000
People like SLC, SNCC, corp went, there was already a movement there when we got there.

01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:04.000
There was already a movement in a lot of these places.

01:26:04.000 --> 01:26:10.000
And NAACP was our legal, mostly our legal.

01:26:10.000 --> 01:26:13.000
We had a lawyer once though, Lennox Hinds (low).

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:14.000
I don't know who he is now.

01:26:14.000 --> 01:26:22.000
But Len was dating Jaila as much as we did looking to tempt the court with the judges.

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:28.000
We getting Jaila and we standing around and you see, Len, what you're doing here, man?

01:26:28.000 --> 01:26:30.000
I bet it here too.

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:35.000
We thought you were outside trying to get us out.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:38.000
Did you move up to New York in 1967?

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:40.000
And I stayed there for a while.

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:42.000
But then I came back to Atlanta.

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:51.000
And when I had a tax cap service in Atlanta, and I represented Capgrave was there as a organizer.

01:26:51.000 --> 01:26:52.000
Capgrave.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:54.000
And then it's about one thing.

01:26:54.000 --> 01:27:00.000
1966, stuck to the comic box, it was the place that John built at the head of Smith.

01:27:00.000 --> 01:27:07.000
The rhetoric shifts, there's more move towards the question of oneself defense.

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:11.000
There's more of Black Power rhetoric comes in and folks talk about this.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:13.000
There's a little bit of a different spirit now.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:15.000
I think it was radical.

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:27.000
You know, that part became more cultural conscious too.

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:33.000
And a lot of people didn't understand everything that was behind it.

01:27:33.000 --> 01:27:38.000
It wasn't just, you know, they heard the word Black Power and they thought about something else.

01:27:38.000 --> 01:27:40.000
But that wasn't what it was about.

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:46.000
It was about lifting ourselves up.

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:53.000
And pretty much, I don't know if any organization, any Black organization,

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:58.000
organization that was mixed like that, that went on the violin, Mars, they went on the violin.

01:27:58.000 --> 01:27:59.000
Excuse me.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:23.000
I don't know if any of the black organizations are either integrated organizations.

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:27.000
Never did a violin.

01:28:27.000 --> 01:28:33.000
They never did a violin demonstration or go after anybody.

01:28:33.000 --> 01:28:36.000
That's violence.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:39.000
What we did in Hale County was self-defense.

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:44.000
There's a difference between self-defense and overt violence.

01:28:44.000 --> 01:28:50.000
And I don't know if any of that, any overt activity.

01:28:50.000 --> 01:28:57.000
Mostly it was cultural and trying to defend ourselves.

01:28:57.000 --> 01:29:00.000
And younger group of people go do different things.

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:04.000
Some of those folks were younger than us even.

01:29:04.000 --> 01:29:05.000
So...

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:08.000
You were on my cultural view of my view.

01:29:08.000 --> 01:29:10.000
I was learning about African black people.

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:11.000
Yeah.

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:12.000
Yeah.

01:29:12.000 --> 01:29:16.000
I'm just saying and then implying in yourself because if you don't think good of yourself,

01:29:16.000 --> 01:29:19.000
nobody's going to think good of you.

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:26.000
And this is when I began to learn more about African American history and African history.

01:29:26.000 --> 01:29:33.000
I got arrested in Atlanta for trying to see a big African dignitary.

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:39.000
I finally got to see one here in Selma when he Mandela came here.

01:29:39.000 --> 01:29:43.000
I was introduced to her by Rose Sanders.

01:29:43.000 --> 01:29:46.000
And I hugged her and I said, I'm so glad to meet you.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:48.000
I don't know what to do.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:53.000
You're the first African dignitary that I got to see without getting arrested.

01:29:53.000 --> 01:29:56.000
I really want to thank you Miss A.

01:29:56.000 --> 01:30:01.000
But you've been so generous of your time.

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:10.000
Well, what I do want to say is that at this time,

01:30:10.000 --> 01:30:16.000
I think it was an honor to have been associated with all of the people that I work with.

01:30:16.000 --> 01:30:21.000
The SCLC people, the NCAA CPP people, the CORE people,

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:30.000
and now the people who are working with the Bridge Crossing Jubilee and the National Voting Rights Museum and Institute

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:34.000
and the Mississippi Civil Rights Veterans.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:45.000
I'm just excited and honored to have been associated with all of these people that I have met and known, marrying there.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:51.000
It's just a whole lot of people we can go on all day.

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:52.000
Well, thank you.

01:30:52.000 --> 01:30:56.000
You've given us a fabulous interview and we really appreciate your taking the time and sitting down with us.

01:30:56.000 --> 01:30:57.000
Thank you.

01:30:57.000 --> 01:30:59.000
Okay. I thank you.

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:09.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
